---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="center">
  <h1><span class="main-gradient">Transport</span> 🚌</h1>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">stdio</h2>
  <ul>
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🖥️ <span class="main-sub-gradient">Local</span> process
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📨 Communication via <span class="main-sub-gradient">stdin/stdout</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment><li>⚡ Zero network, zero overhead</li></p-fragment>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      stdio is the simplest transport: the host spawns the MCP server as a child
      process and communicates via standard input/output. No ports, no network,
      no authentication needed. Perfect for local tools like CLI helpers or
      editor plugins.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">HTTP + SSE</h2>
  <ul>
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🌐 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Remote</span> service
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🔗 Communication via <span class="main-sub-gradient">HTTP + SSE</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment><li>👥 Multiple concurrent clients</li></p-fragment>
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        ☁️ Ideal for <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >server-side deployments</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🏢 Best for <span class="main-sub-gradient">shared APIs</span>, cloud
        &amp; multi-tenant services
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      SSE (Server-Sent Events) is a standard for pushing real-time updates from
      a server to a client over HTTP.
    </p>
    <p>
      HTTP with SSE is for remote servers: the client sends requests over HTTP
      POST and receives streamed responses via SSE. This allows multiple clients
      to connect simultaneously and enables deployment on any infrastructure.
      Choose this when you need a shared API accessible by multiple teams or
      services.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">HTTP + SSE</span> — two channels
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="http-sse.js">
  <code is:raw class="language-javascript">// 1. Open the SSE stream
  // The server will push responses/events here
  const sse = new EventSource('/sse');

  sse.onmessage = (event) => {
    const message = JSON.parse(event.data);
    handle(message);
  };</code>
</pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The older HTTP + SSE transport used two separate channels: a long-lived
      GET request for server-sent events, and a POST endpoint for client
      messages.
    </p>
    <p>
      The session ID connects those two channels on the server side. This works,
      but it adds operational complexity: the server has to keep track of open
      streams, sessions, idle connections and proxy behavior.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="http-sse.js">
  <code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">// 2. Send MCP requests to a separate endpoint
  await fetch('/message?</code><code p-fragment p-effect="highlight" style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">sessionId=abc123'</code><code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">,{
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      jsonrpc: '2.0',
      </code><code p-fragment p-effect="highlight" style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">id: 1,</code><code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">
      method: 'tools/call',
      params: {
        name: 'get-orders',
        arguments: {
          customerId: '123'
        }
      }
    })
  });</code></pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">Streamable HTTP</h2>
  <ul>
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🆕 The <span class="main-sub-gradient">new standard</span> — replaces HTTP
        + SSE
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🔀 Single endpoint, <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >optional streaming</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment><li>🔄 Supports stateless &amp; stateful modes</li></p-fragment>
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        ✅ Better fit for <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >modern infrastructure</span
        > (proxies, load balancers)
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Streamable HTTP is the evolution of HTTP+SSE introduced in the 2025 MCP
      spec revision. A single HTTP endpoint handles both regular
      request/response and streaming via chunked transfer. It works seamlessly
      behind proxies and load balancers that may not support SSE well, and
      supports both stateless (simpler) and stateful (session-based) server
      modes.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1rem;" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Streamable HTTP</span> — one endpoint
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="streamable-http.js">
  <code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">// Single endpoint, regular HTTP request
  const res = await fetch(</code><code p-fragment p-effect="highlight" style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">'/mcp'</code><code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-javascript">, {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      Accept: 'application/json, text/event-stream'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      jsonrpc: '2.0',
      method: 'tools/call',
      params: {
        name: 'get-orders',
        arguments: { customerId: '123' }
      }
    })
  });</code></pre>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The key difference is not just fewer connections: it is a simpler model.
      Streamable HTTP uses one endpoint for MCP messages. The client sends a
      normal HTTP request, and the server can either return a regular JSON
      response or stream events when needed.
    </p>
    <p>
      The client must include an Accept header to indicate support for streaming
      and application/json responses. The server can then choose to send a
      single JSON response or stream events as needed.
    </p>
    <p>
      In stateless mode, there is no session ID to manage and no long-lived GET
      connection sitting idle, which makes it easier to deploy behind modern
      infrastructure.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<style lang="scss">
  ul {
    p-fragment:not(:last-of-type) li {
      margin-block-end: 0.55em;
    }
  }
</style>
